Date: Mon, 6 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency 1 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200011010099.html>

Sixty Die From Sleeping Sickness in Angola
----------------------------------------------
Uige, Angola: More than 60 people died of trypanosomiasis or sleeping
sickness during he last 3 months in the northern Angolan province of Uige,
the Angolan news agency (Angop) reported Wednesday [1 Nov 2000.
Angop quoted the Uige provincial health department as saying that it has
taken urgent measures, including physical elimination of the vector, the
tsetse fly, in the area. It said more than 91 000 tsetse flies had so far
been trapped. The ministry of health said it has dispatched 420 traps and
151 trained personnel to catch the deadly flies in 58 villages in Uige. The
director of the trypanosomiasis control institute, Teofile Jofenado, told
journalists recently that the Angolan government has set aside 4 million US
dollars to combat the disease over the next few years. The amount was part
of the 35 million US dollars the cabinet approved recently to combat
malaria, leprosy, AIDS and sleeping sickness.
